{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488900"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"569"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/569"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.04,0.66,0.05,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83460"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/569"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68351"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1914"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35929"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83460"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal pain and fever, along with a one-month history of increasing abdominal distension. His medical history is significant for chronic liver disease secondary to chronic alcohol dependence, hypertension, atrial fibrillation, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, and temperature 38.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is scleral jaundice. The abdomen is grossly distended, with prominent superficial veins and shifting dullness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal deranged transaminases, bilirubin 40 \u00b5mol/L [2-24], albumin 28 g/L [34-48], and INR 2.5 [0.9-1.2].\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS)","Trimethoprim / sulfamethoxazole","Diagnostic tap and ceftriaxone","Spironolactone","Therapeutic ascitic drain"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stem describes ascites secondary to chronic liver failure. Given the acute fever and abdominal pain, this ascites has likely been complicated by spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP). The first step would be to confirm with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ediagnostic ascitic tap\u003C/strong\u003E. The sample should be collected prior to commencing empirical intravenous antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common causative organisms of SBP are Gram-negative bacteria such as \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella\u003C/em\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used for prophylaxis in the event of recurrent SBP, as it is most specific for these organisms. However, here we are treating an acute episode, where broad-spectrum \u003Cstrong\u003Eceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is preferred for additional coverage of \u003Cem\u003Estreptococci\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is used as a diuretic in the management of ascites, but will not address the infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etherapeutic ascitic drain\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to provide symptomatic relief from large-volume ascites. It may be considered in this case, however the priority is to address the infection in order to prevent sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS)\u003C/strong\u003E is a procedure involving the insertion of a shunt between the portal and hepatic veins. This alleviates portal pressure and is particularly important in the management of oesophageal varices. Although it may help to reduce ascites, TIPS is not used directly in the treatment of SBP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) needs to be excluded in a patient with clinical ascites presenting with a febrile illness.","A diagnostic ascitic tap is essential to confirm SBP and should be performed before starting antibiotics.","Empirical treatment for SBP typically involves broad-spectrum antibiotics such as ceftriaxone."],"references":["Ascites [Internet]. eTG Complete. 2020. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","MacIntosh T. Emergency Management of Spontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis - A Clinical Review. Cureus. 2018 Mar 1;10(3):e2253. doi: 10.7759/cureus.2253. PMID: 29721399; PMCID: PMC5929973. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29721399/","Dever JB, Sheikh MY. Review article: spontaneous bacterial peritonitis--bacteriology, diagnosis, treatment, risk factors and prevention. Aliment Pharmacol Ther. 2015 Jun;41(11):1116-31. doi: 10.1111/apt.13172. Epub 2015 Mar 26. PMID: 25819304. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25819304/","Ameer MA, Foris LA, Mandiga P, et al. Spontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448208/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68351"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"569"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68351"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T18:53:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T18:54:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"569"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83460"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"upda